post_text: Over the past few weeks a host of PCS stakeholders have participated in surveys, meetings and discussions about how we will reopen schools in September. New York State guidelines have mandated that we develop three instructional models: in-person, remote learning and a hybrid of both. We are working on these models while keeping three priority themes in mind: health and safety, academics, and social-emotional well being. The plan we select will be based on Governor Cuomo‚Äôs reopening announcement scheduled for next week. Thank you for your continued patience as we work through this difficult process.

shared_text:
New York Association of Agricultural Educators
June 22 at 4:49 PM ¬∑

We are thrilled to announce that the 2020 Outstanding Early Career Teacher and the recipient of the Teacher Turn the Key Award is KYLIE SMITH.

Kylie is the agricultural teacher at Pavilion Central School in Western New York. She ensures that her classroom provides a safe environment for all students, regardless of background or intellectual ability, to receive a broad education in agriculture. To achieve this, she utilizes inquiry-base, hands-on learning to demonstrate the connections of the agricultural concepts to the real world to the students.

Congratulations Kylie and good luck representing New York at the Region 6 contest and have an amazing time at the 2020 Teacher Turn the Key Conference.

*The Outstanding Early Career Teacher Award is a means of encouraging young teachers to remain in the profession and to recognize their participation in professional activities.

*The Teachers Turn the Key professional development program focuses on providing early-career agriculture teachers with the tools and support they need to grow and flourish in the profession.
text:
Congratulations Miss Smith! What a well-deserved honor!

New York Association of Agricultural Educators
June 22 at 4:49 PM ¬∑

We are thrilled to announce that the 2020 Outstanding Early Career Teacher and the recipient of the Teacher Turn the Key Award is KYLIE SMITH.

Kylie is the agricultural teacher at Pavilion Central School in Western New York. She ensures that her classroom provides a safe environment for all students, regardless of background or intellectual ability, to receive a broad education in agriculture. To achieve this, she utilizes inquiry-base, hands-on learning to demonstrate the connections of the agricultural concepts to the real world to the students.

Congratulations Kylie and good luck representing New York at the Region 6 contest and have an amazing time at the 2020 Teacher Turn the Key Conference.

*The Outstanding Early Career Teacher Award is a means of encouraging young teachers to remain in the profession and to recognize their participation in professional activities.

*The Teachers Turn the Key professional development program focuses on providing early-career agriculture teachers with the tools and support they need to grow and flourish in the profession.

Due to COVID-19 and with an abundance of caution, the Pavilion Central School District has decided to cancel the remaining performances of The Wizard of Oz.
The District is following guidance from the Department of Health that is stating that gatherings with an audience that cannot be controlled should be avoided. An uncontrolled audience means that it could include anyone over the age of 60 and or include someone with a compromised immune system. The District will continue to work with state and federal agencies, and the Genesee County Department of Health to make decisions as guidance on these matters is changing daily.
The District apologizes for any inconvenience, but the primary concern is the health and wellness of all students and staff

On Saturday, the Boys Volleyball team beat #1 School of the Arts 3 to 0.

The team improved to 12 & 7 & advance to the finals.
Cameron Milligan dominated the match with 27 kills, 13 digs & 4 aces. Cole Tillotson had a solid all around performance with 24 assists, 5 digs and 4 aces. Ty Heineman tallied 7 digs to go with 3 aces and 2 kills.

The team plays 6 pm TONIGHT against #2 Midlakes in the Class B2 Finals at Webster Schroeder.

Alexa Wolcott won her meet by 20 seconds winning in 20:32 Tuesday at Oatka Creek.

post_text:
The boys varsity volleyball team went 2 & 0 this weekend to improve to 7 and 3 on the season.

On Friday the team defeated Wayne in 4 sets behind 21 kills from Cameron Milligan, 6 kills from Ty Heineman, 4 kills from Cole Tillotson & 3 kills from Collin Graham.

On Saturday the team took care of North Rose Wolcott in 3 straight sets with a solid crowd of fans! Cameron Milligan led the way with a solid all around performance of 27 kills, 5 digs & 6 aces. Cole Tillotson set up 26 assists in the match. Dan Nichols added 4 aces.

Please come out tomorrow night with the boys taking on Canandaigua for a 5 pm JV match with Varsity to follow.

post_text:
PAVILION OVER DANSVILLE
Rex Eighmey and the Pavilion girls continue to surprise as they defeated Dansville (5-6) Monday in five sets ‚Äî winning 25-17,22-25, 25-18, 14-25,and 25-9 in LCAA crossover action.

Pavilion, who improved to 9-2 on the year, was led by Lauren Kingsley with 16 kills and three blocks while Shannon Campbell added a game high 27 assists.

Addy Milligan chipped in 12 digs and 10 kills for the winners.

In the fifth and deciding set, Paige Landers had 13 straight service points including three aces to turn a 5-4 lead into a 20-4 advantage.

Pavilion has no seniors on the roster.
